      <!-- What it does -->
      <div class="section" data-reveal>
        <div class="section-label">Section 01</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">What Spanberger just signed</h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            On Thursday, May 14, 2026, Gov. Abigail Spanberger signed Senate
            Bill 749 into law. It is the most sweeping firearms restriction
            Virginia has ever enacted. Starting <strong>July 1, 2026</strong>,
            it will be a crime to <strong
              >import, sell, manufacture, purchase, or transfer</strong
            > any firearm Virginia now classifies as an &ldquo;assault firearm,&rdquo;
            along with any magazine, belt, drum, or feed strip that holds more than
            15 rounds.
          </p>
          <p>
            Virginia is now the <strong>11th state</strong> to enact some form of
            assault weapons ban. The General Assembly passed identical versions of
            the bill in March (Senate 21&ndash;19, House 59&ndash;35). Spanberger
            sent it back in April with more than a dozen amendments that would have
            broadened the ban further &mdash; most notably striking the word &ldquo;fixed&rdquo;
            from the rifle and pistol magazine-capacity clause. At the April 22 reconvened
            session, the General Assembly
            <strong>rejected her amendments</strong>, passing the bill &ldquo;by
            for the day&rdquo; in both chambers, which returned it to her in its
            original form. On May 14 she signed the legislature's version
            unchanged.
          </p>
          <p>
            A violation is a <strong>Class 1 misdemeanor</strong> — up to 12 months
            in jail, up to a $2,500 fine, and a mandatory three-year prohibition on
            purchasing, possessing, or transporting any firearm following conviction.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-danger">
          <div class="callout-label">The Headline Numbers</div>
          <p>
            <strong>Effective date:</strong> July 1, 2026. <strong
              >Penalty:</strong
            > Class 1 misdemeanor, up to 12 months + $2,500 + 3-year firearm prohibition.
            <strong>Magazine cap:</strong> 15 rounds. <strong>Age floor:</strong
            > 21. <strong>Lawsuits filed within 24 hours:</strong> three &mdash; a
            joint SAF/NRA/FPC federal suit, an NRA state suit, and a DOJ federal suit.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- The six categories -->
      <div class="section" data-reveal>
        <div class="section-label">Section 02</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">The six categories</h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            Virginia uses a <strong>features-based test</strong>, not a list of
            named models. A firearm becomes an &ldquo;assault firearm&rdquo;
            when it matches a defined action plus a defined magazine type plus a
            required number of physical features. There are six categories.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">1</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">
              Centerfire rifle or pistol with a <em>fixed</em> magazine capacity over
              15 rounds
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            <strong>Semi-automatic centerfire rifles and pistols.</strong> No features
            required &mdash; but the magazine must be <strong>fixed</strong> (built
            into the firearm), not detachable. Spanberger's amendment to remove &ldquo;fixed&rdquo;
            was rejected, so this clause as enacted catches almost nothing on the
            modern market. The detachable-magazine firearms run through Categories
            2 and 3.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">2</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">
              Centerfire rifle with a detachable magazine plus any one feature
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            <strong>Semi-automatic centerfire rifles</strong> that accept a detachable
            magazine and have <strong>any one</strong> of the listed offensive features.
          </div>
          <div class="cat-features">
            <div class="cat-features-label">Triggering features</div>
            <div class="cat-features-list">
              Folding/telescoping/collapsible stock &middot; pistol grip
              protruding beneath the action &middot; second handgrip (forward
              grip) &middot; threaded barrel &middot; grenade launcher
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">3</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">
              Centerfire pistol with a detachable magazine plus two features
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            <strong>Semi-automatic centerfire pistols</strong> that accept a detachable
            magazine and have <strong>two or more</strong> of the listed features.
          </div>
          <div class="cat-features">
            <div class="cat-features-label">Triggering features</div>
            <div class="cat-features-list">
              Second handgrip &middot; magazine outside the grip &middot; barrel
              shroud &middot; threaded barrel &middot; buffer tube/arm brace
              &middot; &ldquo;any characteristic of like kind&rdquo;
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">4</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">
              Semi-auto shotgun with any one of the listed features
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            <strong>Semi-automatic shotguns.</strong> One feature is enough.
          </div>
          <div class="cat-features">
            <div class="cat-features-label">Triggering features</div>
            <div class="cat-features-list">
              Folding, telescoping, or collapsible stock &middot; thumbhole
              stock &middot; pistol grip protruding beneath the action &middot;
              ability to accept a detachable magazine &middot; fixed magazine
              over 15 rounds
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">5</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">Revolving-cylinder shotguns</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            The design alone qualifies. No features required, no capacity test.
            Streetsweeper-style and similar.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cat">
          <div class="cat-num-row">
            <div class="cat-num">6</div>
            <div class="cat-headline">
              Anything modified after July 1 to fit the prior categories
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-body">
            Catch-all. Any firearm <strong>modified after enactment</strong> so that
            it meets any of the preceding five categories becomes an assault firearm
            by operation of law. Aftermarket parts will be policed by this clause.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Banned by name -->
