      <!-- The word she tried to delete -->
      <div class="section" data-reveal>
        <div class="section-label">Section 05</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">
          The one word she <span class="red">tried to delete</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            That is what the law covers. Here is what Spanberger wanted it to
            cover.
          </p>
          <p>
            Category 1 &mdash; semi-automatic centerfire rifles and pistols with
            a <strong>fixed magazine capacity</strong> greater than 15 rounds &mdash;
            is almost nothing on its own. &ldquo;Fixed&rdquo; means built into the
            firearm, not detachable. Almost no modern rifle or pistol on the market
            has a fixed magazine over 15 rounds. The clause as written catches very
            little.
          </p>
          <p>
            Spanberger's April 14 amendments would have <strong
              >deleted the word &ldquo;fixed.&rdquo;</strong
            > The clause would then have read that any semi-automatic centerfire rifle
            or pistol with a magazine capacity over 15 rounds qualifies as an assault
            firearm &mdash; including detachable magazines, including magazines not
            even inserted. NRA-ILA argued that reading would have swept in essentially
            every common centerfire semi-auto in Virginia, including Glock 17s with
            factory magazines and 1911s with extended Wilson magazines.
          </p>
          <p>
            The General Assembly killed it. At the April 22 reconvened session,
            both chambers passed the bill <strong
              >&ldquo;by for the day&rdquo;</strong
            > on her amendments &mdash; a procedural move that rejects the governor's
            changes and returns the bill in its original form. Cardinal News led with
            &ldquo;General Assembly rejects more than a dozen of Spanberger's amendments.&rdquo;
            The word &ldquo;fixed&rdquo; stayed in.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="strike-card">
          <div class="strike-card-label">
            What Spanberger proposed &mdash; April 14
          </div>
          <div class="strike-card-quote">
            &ldquo;A semi-automatic centerfire rifle or pistol with a <span
              class="struck">fixed</span
            > magazine capacity in excess of 15 rounds.&rdquo;
          </div>
          <div class="strike-card-note">
            Strike one word, broaden the ban from &ldquo;essentially
            nothing&rdquo; to &ldquo;essentially every common centerfire
            semi-auto.&rdquo;
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="strike-card" style="border-color:var(--green);">
          <div class="strike-card-label" style="color:var(--green);">
            What the General Assembly enacted &mdash; April 22, signed May 14
          </div>
          <div class="strike-card-quote">
            &ldquo;A semi-automatic centerfire rifle or pistol with a <span
              class="kept">fixed</span
            > magazine capacity in excess of 15 rounds.&rdquo;
          </div>
          <div class="strike-card-note">
            The legislature rejected her amendments. &ldquo;Fixed&rdquo; stayed
            in. The signed law is sweeping &mdash; it just isn't every common
            semi-auto in Virginia.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pullquote 2 -->
      <div class="pullquote" data-reveal>
        She pushed for the <span class="red">maximal version</span>. The
        legislature wouldn't go along. What got signed is still sweeping &mdash;
        it just isn't every common semi-auto in Virginia.
      </div>

